      <hedline>
        <hl1>Directed by Losey</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Henry Colman letter on Robert Simonson's June 4 tribute to T Edward Hambleton recalls that Joseph Losey directed 1947 production of Bertolt Brecht's Galileo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The article on T. Edward Hambleton was of special nostalgic and historical import for me. You see, thanks to the trust of Mr. Hambleton, I was hired as an assistant stage manager and played a bit part (No. 2 Scribe) in the 1947 production of Brecht's ''Galileo,'' starring Charles Laughton.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The article on T. Edward Hambleton was of special nostalgic and historical import for me. You see, thanks to the trust of Mr. Hambleton, I was hired as an assistant stage manager and played a bit part (No. 2 Scribe) in the 1947 production of Brecht's ''Galileo,'' starring Charles Laughton.</p>
        <p>I need to set the record straight, however, in that Joseph Losey, who later went on to direct such memorable films as ''The Boy With Green Hair'' and ''The Servant,'' was the director of ''Galileo.'' But in giving that credit to Bertolt Brecht, Mr. Simonson did not miss the mark by much. I have this indelible memory of rehearsal, with Brecht marching up to the stage and carefully and in great detail acting out for the actor every nuance and movement of the scene, though Brecht spoke little English.</p>
        <p>HENRY COLMAN  Venice, Calif.</p>
        <p>T. EDWARD HAMBLETON</p>
      </block>
